2. PyOD as an MCP Tool Server (Architectural Option)
The proposal explicitly mentions this. Since you already have mcp_clients.py and the MCP pattern built, PyOD can run as a separate MCP sidecar process — isolated memory, independently scalable, hot-loaded models. Your existing BaseExtractionMCP pattern is exactly the right template.

3. GE Ephemeral Context — The Root Problem
Your gx_validation_specialist.py uses EphemeralDataContext — GE expectations rebuild from scratch every run and are never stored. This means:

No regression detection ("this expectation passed last week, fails now")
Auto-rule authoring can't know what rules already exist
No trend tracking in GE's DataDocs
Fix: FileSystemDataContext — one line change, massive downstream impact. This needs to happen before auto-rule authoring, COPOD, or any cross-run learning.

4. The "Fraud" Section Was Unfairly Dismissed
The proposal is describing data anomaly detection with quarantine — not fraud classification. anomaly_score > 0.9 → quarantine is 100% a DQ action. The word "fraud" is misleading but the technical approach is valid. The right framing: detect records that look unlike all historical data, quarantine them regardless of cause (error, migration bug, injection, test data, or actual fraud).

5. Three Time-Series Detection Types Were Missed
Beyond seasonal volume, ADTK's PersistAD catches gradual concept drift (mean drifting slowly over weeks — invisible to single-run comparisons), LevelShiftAD catches permanent regime changes (volume drops permanently after a system event), and gap detection catches missing pipeline executions.

